<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://groups.msn.com/_Secure/0UQDZAvEZO00g9M*!6iyVLQ09mpS*ZPd2Rp6ZIWzqL0ujzIKF8WCuVoelKGqy05gAMAtOV9Uw8pItiRYCdYaZJ4Rc!MhNSPhku9uuiQ0MXtbEJEQIkD*SMdrxtatntdkK/flag_cdn.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=peaches116>peaches116</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Dream Writer<br>40 pts.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 640<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/9/03 11:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=38>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.onerefuge.com/stitch.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Just a reminder....</span><hr size=1> Wow, my translation of 1 Corinthians seems a bit different.  The paragraph starts in verse 10, so I'll start there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>10</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> By the grace God has given me, I laid a foundation as an expert builder, and someone else is building on it.  But each one should be careful how he builds.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>11</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> For no one can lay any foundation other than the one already laid, which is Jesus Christ.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>12</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> If any man builds on this foundation using gold, silver, costly stones, wood, hay or straw, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>13</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> his work will be shown for what it is, because the Day will bring it to light.  It will be revealed with fire, and the fire will test the quality of each man's work.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>14</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> If what he has built survives, he will receive his reward.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>15</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> If it is burned up, he will suffer loss; he himself will be saved, but only as one escaping through the flames.<br>
(1 Cor. 3:10-15 NIV)<br>
<br>
That passage in 1 Cor. 3, in context is a warning about causing divisions in the church.  It says that the Lord will reveal the quality of our work, but this is something consistent throughout scripture.  We read passages that talk about storing up treasures in Heaven.  I don't have a clue what &quot;treasures in Heaven&quot; are, and I doubt any of us will until we get there.  But the point on that is - we're all saved, despite how many treasures we have, if we belong to Jesus.  And I could use the progression of the beattitudes here to help illustrate my point, but it's a rather long illustration.  The person with no treasures is just as much saved as the person who has built up many treasures.  And this passage in 1 Cor. states that.  Paul's basically warning these people to be productive so that their work is not in vain.  It's like with Cain and Able and the sacrifice God accepted and the sacrifice He rejected.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>One place would be here, &quot;it is appointed for men to die once, and after that comes judgment&quot; (Heb 9:27).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I guess I'm not fond of the term &quot;day of judgment&quot; because it sounds harsh.  But even Rev. 20 talks about the dead being judged.  The term sounds scary.  To be told that you are going to be judged by God someday - hey, I want to run and hide under the nearest rock.  To think of God's judgment coming down upon me - I tend to think of judgment as wrath.  Yet the Bible tells me not to fear because I belong to Jesus and even if I do nothing to extend the kingdom of Heaven and to store up treasures in Heaven, I know I'm still going to spend eternity with the Lord.  So there's comfort there.<br>
<br>
When 1 Cor. 3 says &quot;but only as one escaping through the flames&quot; in my translation or &quot;but like someone escaping through a wall of flames&quot; in your translation; what that tells me is that those are the Christians who did nothing to further the Kingdom of Heaven, who didn't store up any treasures in Heaven, and are as though they had just been saved and hadn't had the time yet to mature in their faith, whether they had just become Christians or had been Christians for many years.  It's no indication that they were punished for not doing good works in God's eyes.  It's symbolizing the level of their faith in Christ - they were still infants in the Lord as just before that paragraph, Paul wrote in 1 Cor. 3:2:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>I gave you milk, not solid food, for you were not yet ready for it.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Paul is warning them that if they don't mature in their faith, then everything their doing isn't going to stand the test of God and when they finally face God, in regards to all other believers, they will be considered infants in the faith, as those just saved from the fires of hell who were not yet mature.<br>
<br>
But this is getting into aspects of Heaven and treasures in Heaven and maturity among believers and I honestly don't understand it.  I have no idea what &quot;treasures in Heaven&quot; will be.  I don't know what that means.  And basically that's because I don't understand how things will work in Heaven.  If anyone understands these things, please enlighten me.  I'm not sure exactly what works store treasures up in Heaven.  Is it just saving souls?  That makes me nervous because for as much as I've shared with people, I've never actually led a person to the Lord.  Which is a bummer really, because I'd really like to do that.  I don't know, this I'm sure should be a topic in and of itself.<br>
<br>
(edited to fix the 1 Cor. 3:2 verse - it's milk, not mile. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Elves seldom give unguarded advice, for advice is a dangerous gift, even from the wise to the wise, and all courses may run ill.&quot; - Gildor (LOTR: FOTR)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=peaches116>peaches116</A> at: 11/10/03 12:56 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wordwolf>WordWolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Sir WordWolf,<br>Keeper of Odd Knowledge,<br>Bachelor-at-Arms</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 116<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/10/03 12:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Just a reminder....</span><hr size=1> Peaches,<br>
<br>
Personally, I LIKE the terms &quot;Judgement Day&quot; and <br>
&quot;Day of Judgement&quot;. <br>
I know some people have ascribed ominous overtones to<br>
the terms (like &quot;Terminator 2: Judgement Day&quot;, a <br>
 frightening apocalyptic vision that must be stopped).<br>
However, I like the terms for 2 reasons of my own.<br>
<br>
A) Of all the terms in the Bible, these terms have been<br>
ascribed the least amount of baggage.  The term <br>
&quot;apocalypse&quot; comes from the term for &quot;revealing&quot; or <br>
&quot;unveiling&quot;-the unveiling of the events, which is the writing<br>
of the Book of Revelation. However, everyone here has<br>
heard people associate the term &quot;apocalypse&quot; with <br>
cataclysmic global disaster. (Not necessarily without <br>
reason.)  <br>
B) It's a simple term which I believe correctly reflects the<br>
events as outlined in Scripture, without adding in baggage<br>
of its own.  <br>
<br>
Anyone frightened of the judgement of God should remember<br>
that a judgement can go in your favour or against you.<br>
Neither direction is implied by the term &quot;judgement&quot; any<br>
more than &quot;a verdict was rendered&quot; tells you WHAT the<br>
verdict was.  Other terms used to refer to the same events,<br>
although translated from the same Greek words, carry FAR<br>
more baggage into English (&quot;condemnation&quot; and <br>
&quot;damnation&quot; are the ones I found, both translated from the<br>
EXACT same Greek words translated &quot;judgement&quot;).<br>
Also, if one is reluctant to face judgement of God, one should<br>
find out a bit more about this judgement-what its standards<br>
are, what its criteria are, what its possible consequences<br>
are.  If one is not happy with one's standing before God,<br>
they would do well to obey God more and defy Him less.<br>
I, for one, look forward to the Day of Judgement-at least,<br>
I look forward to my own.  (Then again, I'm a nut.)<br>
<br>
I'M NOT AIMING THAT AT ANYONE SPECIFIC, NEITHER HERE<br>
NOR ANYWHERE ELSE.  <br>
I was stating my general position and running thru the<br>
hypotheticals.  <br>
Personally, if I were to trade places with any of the posters<br>
here, I doubt I'd wake up in a sweat over the thought of the<br>
Judgement of God, either. So, there!<br>
<br>
So, that's why I like the terms.  Feel free to disagree with<br>
me.  <br>
<br>
=========================<br>
Esdras,<br>
can you please cut-and-paste your last points on this<br>
thread into the other one? <br>
I'd love to address them there, I think they're more than<br>
appropriate there, and I think they are necessary for the<br>
discussion there.<br>
<br>
Peaches, if I have my druthers, we'll address I Cor 3 on that<br>
very thread as well, and I'm looking forward to it.<br>
(Then again, I'm a nut.)<br>
<br>
<br>
