Actually, what I really feel frightened by is your spelling. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   There's no e in the word judgment. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   (The being frightened by your spelling is just some fun teasing.)<br>
<br>
I think it's because the Bible warns so strictly against us judging others and it's considered preferable if we don't have to go into court and face a judge for things we have done - it makes the word &quot;judgment&quot; seem very dark and very negative.  So it's harder for me to remind myself that God's judgment is good.  But then at the same time, there is a healthy fear of the Lord.  To recognize His holiness in light of my sinfulness - standing in His judgment doesn't sound like a pleasurable thing.  Though the Bible gives promises to those of us who belong to Him that we have nothing to fear if we belong to Jesus.  But the fear of the Lord in recognizing His holiness in contrast to our sinfulness is quite overwhelming - at least it is for me.  As much as I call God &quot;Daddy&quot; and blow kisses to Him at night, I do believe I have that healthy fear of the Lord in me that I never lose sight of His power and might and awesomeness.<br>
<br>
Rather than Judgment Day, I like the way 1 Cor. 1:8 words it in the NIV.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>He will keep you strong to the end, so that you will be blameless on the day of the Lord Jesus Christ.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I like calling it &quot;The Day of the Lord&quot; rather than &quot;Judgment Day.&quot;  To me, Judgment Day just has too many negative connotations to it.  But to say &quot;The Day of the Lord&quot; sounds good - because God is good.  And to say &quot;The Day of the Lord Jesus Christ&quot; is better because the Bible says that that every spirit who acknowledges Jesus for who He is acknowledges God.  Not everyone who believes in God acknowledges Jesus. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
