I object to someone's statement that if we didn't have<br>
tradition, we would have no Bible.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The Bible was written by men, it did not fall out of the sky, in a bonded leather edition.  Among all of the writings certain writings were picked over a period of time, not all of the books had an easy time making the cut, and it took almost 400 years to get what we call the New Testament.  The great Codex Sinaititicus had Barnabas and The Shepard as part of the New Testament, books that eventually did not make the cut.  Revelation and Hebrews were a compromise between the west and the east, the east wanted Hebrews and the west wanted Revelation.  Revelation was so late in making the cut that it is not in any of the Eastern Church's lectionaries.  The Church with the Apostolic Tradition picked the books, because as St Paul said it is the Church which is the Pillar and Bulwark of Truth.  Without the Apostolic Tradition there would have been no way to pick among the various writings.  Even the Gospels themselves preserve the Tradition of Apostolic preaching.<br>
Jeff the Finn<br>
