in 1 Corinthians 15:3 Paul uses the technical words for receiving and handing on traditions.<br>
<br>
My study notes say:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I delivered to you as of first importance what I also received.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Here Paul links himself with early Christian tradition.  He was not its originator, nor did he receive it directly from the Lord.  His source was other Christians.  The verbs he uses are technical terms for receiving and transmitting tradition.  What follows is the heart of the gospel;  that Christ died for our sins, that He was buried and that He was raised from the dead<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:maroon;><b>Administrator<br>Sir Esdras,<br>Master, Knights of the Realm,<br>Peacekeeper Extraordinaire,<br>Canadian, eh.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 596<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/10/03 11:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=50>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Just a reminder....</span><hr size=1> Regarding the translation of the word &quot;tradition&quot; or &quot;teaching&quot;, this is what I found from the various versions checking at Blue Letter Bible.<br>
<br>
For 1 Cor 11:2<br>
<br>
Teaching, NLT; Tradition, NKJV; Tradition, NASB; Tradition, RSV; Ordinances, Webster's; Deliverances, Young's; Directives, Darby's; Tradition, ASV; Tradition, HNV; Ordinances, KJV; Teachings, NIV; Tradition, NAB; Ordinances, Douay-Rheims.<br>
<br>
The word being translated is paradosis<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>1) giving up, giving over<br>
a) the act of giving up<br>
b) the surrender of cities<br>
<br>
2) a giving over which is done by word of mouth or in writing, i.e. tradition by instruction, narrative, precept, etc.<br>
a) objectively, that which is delivered, the substance of a teaching<br>
b) of the body of precepts, esp. ritual, which in the opinion of the later Jews were orally delivered by Moses and orally transmitted in unbroken succession to subsequent generations, which precepts, both illustrating and expanding the written law, as they did were to be obeyed with equal reverence<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For the passage in 2 Thess 2:15,<br>
<br>
Everything, NLT; Tradition, NKJV; Tradition, NASB; Tradition, RSV; Tradition, Webster's; Deliverances, Young's; Instructions, Darby's; Tradition, ASV; Tradition, HNV; Tradtion, KJV; Teachings, NIV; Tradition, NAB; Tradition, Douay-Rheims.<br>
<br>
It was also the same word being translated - paradosis.<br>
<br>
The majority of translations seem to lean towards tradition.  However, it's relatively apparent that the concpet of tradition is not portrayed negatively every time in the Bible. <br>
